@page "/Account/Login"
@layout AccountLayout
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Antiforgery
@using ServantSync.Services
@inject IAntiforgery Antiforgery

<PageTitle>Sign in · ServantSync</PageTitle>

@* Round-SPLASH (this): marketing splash hero above the Sign-in form.
   The use of servantsync-marketing.svg (not
   servantsync-mark.svg) is intentional per the two-asset contract
   in BRANDING.md — this is a marketing surface. *@
<WordmarkSplash Width="180"
                FigureClass="text-center mt-4 mb-4" />

<h1 class="h3 mb-3">Sign in</h1>

@* Round-AN (this): this page is now static-SSR with a plain HTML
   form posting to /Account/PerformLogin. The previous shape was
   @rendermode InteractiveServer + <EditForm OnValidSubmit=HandleLogin>
   which routed the submit through Blazor's SignalR circuit; inside
   the OnValidSubmit handler SignInManager.PasswordSignInAsync tried
   to write the auth cookie against the SignalR-cached HttpContext
   (whose Response had already streamed the initial page render),
   surfacing "Headers are read-only, response has already started."

   The minimal API endpoint /Account/PerformLogin runs against the
   FRESH HttpContext of the form POST, so SignInManager writes the
   cookie to a Response that hasn't started. Cookie write succeeds.
   After success, the endpoint redirects to the safe ReturnUrl.
   After failure, the endpoint redirects back to /Account/Login
   with ?error=... so the same page can re-render the alert below. *@

@if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Error))
{
    <div class="alert alert-danger py-2 small mb-3">
        @switch (Error)
        {
            case "locked":
                <text>Account is locked out.</text>
                break;
            case "invalid":
            default:
                <text>Invalid email or password.</text>
                break;
        }
    </div>
}

<form method="post" action="/Account/PerformLogin">
    <input type="hidden" name="returnUrl" value="@(ReturnUrl ?? "/")" />
    <input type="hidden" name="__RequestVerificationToken" value="@Antiforgery.GetAndStoreTokens(HttpContext).RequestToken" />

    <div class="form-floating mb-3">
        <input id="email" name="email" type="email" inputmode="email" class="form-control" autocomplete="username" required />
        <label for="email">Email</label>
    </div>
    <div class="form-floating mb-3">
        <input id="password" name="password" type="password" class="form-control" autocomplete="current-password" required />
        <label for="password">Password</label>
    </div>
    <div class="form-check mb-3">
        <input id="remember" name="remember" type="checkbox" class="form-check-input" />
        <label class="form-check-label" for="remember">Remember me</label>
    </div>

    <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary w-100">Sign in</button>
</form>

<p class="mt-3 mb-0">
    Don't have an account? <a href="@($"Account/Register?returnUrl={Uri.EscapeDataString(ReturnUrl ?? "/")}")">Register</a>
</p>
<p class="mb-0">
    <a href="Account/ForgotPassword">Forgot your password?</a>
</p>

@* Round-FR-LOGIN-FIX-A (this): clear any stale antiforgery cookie before
   GetAndStoreTokens mints a fresh anonymous-bound token. The throw site
   we caught in prod (user's verbatim log dump on 2026-07-09) was:

     Microsoft.AspNetCore.Antiforgery.AntiforgeryValidationException:
       The provided antiforgery token was meant for a different
       claims-based user than the current user.
       at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Antiforgery.DefaultAntiforgery.ValidateTokens(...)
       at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Antiforgery.DefaultAntiforgery.ValidateRequestAsync(...)
       at Program.<Main>$>b__0_7>d.MoveNext()   -- the PerformLogin lambda

   ASP.NET 9 Identity binds each antiforgery cookie's internal ClaimUid
   to the current HttpContext.User on first mint. If the browser hits
   /Account/Login GET carrying a cookie minted against a different (or
   anonymous-then-authenticated-then-anonymous) identity -- which
   happens persistently across F1-tier ACA cold-starts / cookie-domain
   quirks / a previous sign-out that didn't clear the antiforgery cookie
   -- then POSTs with that stale token, the validator throws instead of
   exposing a CSRF hole. The user-facing symptom is "the login has an
   error ... yet you can still navigate." The "still navigate" part is
   the user's PRIOR auth cookie surviving the throw (the throw fires
   BEFORE SignInManager.PasswordSignInAsync, so no new cookie is
   written; the existing cookie just keeps working for static-SSR
   nav links that don't POST).

   The fix: at the top of the page's OnInitialized, iterate the request's
   cookies and delete every one whose key starts with the framework's
   antiforgery cookie-name prefix. The next render's
   @Antiforgery.GetAndStoreTokens(...) call will mint a fresh anonymous
   token tied to the *current* HttpContext.User on the same Response.
   See the matching ChangeLog entry on Register.razor for the parallel
   coverage. Scope: this fix is intentionally limited to Login.razor +
   Register.razor -- the four InteractiveServer Account pages
   (ForgotPassword / ResetPassword / ChangePassword / Manage) submit via
   Blazor's SignalR circuit, not via MapPost endpoints, so they bypass
   the Perform*ValidateRequest pipeline entirely. Touching
   Response.Cookies inside an InteractiveServer component during a
   connected circuit would also crash, so we deliberately don't apply
   this to them. *@

@code {
    [SupplyParameterFromQuery] public string? ReturnUrl { get; set; }
    [SupplyParameterFromQuery(Name = "error")] public string? Error { get; set; }
    [CascadingParameter] private HttpContext HttpContext { get; set; } = default!;

    // Round-FR-LOGIN-FIX-A (this): delete every antiforgery cookie the
    // request carries. We iterate by prefix because the actual cookie
    // name has a hash suffix (.AspNetCore.Antiforgery.<hash>) that depends
    // on appPath + authScheme. The prefix is the framework default
    // (AntiforgeryOptions default, equivalent to
    // AntiForgeryDefaults.CookieNamePrefix). Static-SSR pages execute
    // OnInitialized exactly once per HTTP request -- not per interactive
    // re-render -- so this fires once per page load. Safe to delete
    // before the same render's @Antiforgery.GetAndStoreTokens(...) call
    // re-mints an anonymous-bound token (the Delete queues an expired
    // Set-Cookie header; GetAndStoreTokens queues a fresh one; the
    // browser processes them in order).
    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        const string prefix = ".AspNetCore.Antiforgery.";
        foreach (var key in HttpContext.Request.Cookies.Keys)
        {
            if (key.StartsWith(prefix, StringComparison.Ordinal))
            {
                HttpContext.Response.Cookies.Delete(key);
            }
        }
    }
}
